 A systematic study of the extracted parameters like volume ($V$),
 temperature ($T$) and Tsallis non-extensive parameter ($q$), is made
 with identified particle mass. The values of extracted parameters can
 be found in Table.~\ref{table1} of the appendix. We have recalculated
 the radius of the freeze-out volume, assuming a spherical fireball
 and have plotted the radius as a function of identified particle
 mass. Figs. ~\ref{fig7} and ~\ref{fig8} show the common mass
 dependent variation of the parameters at $\sqrt{s_{\rm NN}}$ = 200 GeV and  $\sqrt{s_{\rm NN}}$ = 2.76 TeV. The $\chi^{2}/ndf$ obtained by minimization in TMinuit are shown in Figs. ~\ref{fig5} and ~\ref{fig6}. We have then  compared the peripheral heavy-ion collisions with that of $p+p$ collisions at the same centre of mass energies to understand the thermodynamic properties of the produced systems.

 \begin{figure}[H]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{auau_simple_tsallis1.pdf} 
\caption{(color online) $\chi^{2}/ndf$ values are shown for most peripheral Au+Au and $p+p$ collisions at $\sqrt{\mathrm{s}_{NN}}$= 200 GeV using Eq.~\ref{eq6} as a fit function.} 
\label{fig5}
\end{center}
\end{figure}


