Then we make a mass dependent study of these parameters. Figs.~\ref{fig20} and~\ref{fig21} represent the behaviour of the extracted parameters. 
The parameters like volume, temperature and $q$ show a similar mass dependent behaviour as that of the parameters obtained from the fitting using Eq.~\ref{eq5} and Eq.~\ref{eq6}. 
Here we have introduced an additional radial flow parameter ($\beta$). 
Figs. ~\ref{fig20} and \ref{fig21} show the decrease of radial flow with increase of particle mass, which is a signature of hydrodynamic evolution of the system created in high energy collisions. It could be observed that by the inclusion of radial flow, the value of the $q$ parameter is becoming less, as compared to the other forms of Tsallis distribution, while describing the $p_{\rm T}$-spectra. This may hint that the non-extensivity is shared by the dynamics of the system.   

